column12: FLUIDIC DEVICES
column13: 1,222,368. Fluid logic devices. BRITISH AIRCRAFT CORP. Ltd. 5 Dec., 1968 [7 Dec., 1967], No. 55686/67. Heading G4P. A binary fluidic logic device which may form one stage of a shift register or counter comprises elements A, B, C respectively having input 10 and outputs 12, 14; input 27 and outputs 28, 30; input 34 and outputs 36, 38. Element A is monostable. A pulse at 10 normally flows to 12, but in the presence of a control signal at 16 flows to 14. Element B is bi-stable. Element C is monostable and receives at input 34 a signal whose presence or absence represents 1 or 0. In the absence of a control signal at 24 the input signal passes to output 36. When employed as one stage of a shift register, if there is an O-bit signal at input 34 a shift pulse at 10 passes via 12 into 24 and into 26 to cause the power jet of bi-stable B to exit at output 30 to represent a O-bit. Output 30 is connected to the input 34 of the next stage of the register. If there is a 1-bit signal at 34 the shift pulse at 10 leaves A by 14, part flowing through 20 and 16 to maintain bias on the shift pulse and part flowing to 22 to cause the power jet of bi-stable B to exit at output 28, the lack of flow at 30 representing a 1-bit. Passages Y, Z shown in skeleton may be used to set all bi-stables B in the register to "O" on applying a pulse to the Z passages, or to reset them to "1" by pulsing the Y passages. When employed as a stage in a counter input 34 of element C is connected to the output 30 of the element B. Successive input pulses at 10 set bi-stable B alternately to 1 and 0, the bi-stable being coupled by meansnot shown to the input 10 of the next stage.

column12: METHOD FOR DETECTING CONFLICTS BETWEEN AIRCRAFT
column13: A method for detecting conflicts between aircraft flying in controlled airspace. The method determines whether pairs of aircraft flight routes violate a predetermined proximity test. The separation of pairs of aircraft whose flight routes do not violate the proximity test is assured. For pairs of aircraft whose flight routes violate the proximity test, the method calculates the parts of their flight routes that breach the separation threshold, the conflict paths ( 406, 408 ). The conflict paths are stored. The method determines the portions of aircraft trajectories corresponding to the conflict paths. The separation of aircraft that have flown past their conflict paths is assured. The separation time and separation altitude of pairs of aircraft that have not flown past their conflict paths are calculated. The separation time and separation altitude are used to determine future circumstances whereby the pairs of aircraft may lose separation.
column15: BARKER KENNETH FREDERICK MILES

column12: Method for detecting conflicts between aircraft
column13: For pairs of aircraft whose 2-D or 3-D flight routes 402, 404 violate a proximity test, the parts of their flight routes that breach a horizontal separation threshold 308 are identified as conflict paths 406, 408. Aircraft conflicts are then identified for portions of the trajectories corresponding to the conflict paths (Figs.6-7). Thus portions of the trajectories corresponding to positions outside the conflict paths may be eliminated from the conflict detection, increasing computational efficiency. Time separation and altitude separation of pairs of aircraft that have not flown past their conflict paths may be used to predict loss of separation. Graphical warning indications for pairs of hazarding aircraft may show time separation (1616, Fig.16) and rate of change thereof. Conflict paths may be pre-determined, stored and used later for conflict detection in an air traffic control system.
column15: BARKER KENNETH FREDERICK MILES

A dowelling machine comprises a table 20 upon which a workpiece 3 having a pre-bored hole 2 is clamped, a dowel holder 16 from one end of which a dowel 1 may project, a glue pot 25 and an applicator 26, means 76, 80 for removing the applicator from the glue and moving it past the end of the dowel, and means 21 for driving a dowel into a bored hole. As the cloth is drawn spirally round the cylinder, the stationary, rotary, or other cutter D, set obliquely to the cylinder, cuts the cloth into a strip, which is prevented from contracting laterally by the spiked bands or equivalent devices. The bands G, H are driven by a roller B' and pass round guide-rollers g<1>, h<1>, h<2>, h<3>, h<4> mounted inside the cylinder A so that the bands emerge from the cylinder flush with its surface to grip the cloth. If the strip is to be divided into two or more strips, other cutters are mounted on a shaft preferably between the rollers B', C. A pressing-roller maybe mounted above the cylinder in front of the knife D to direct the cloth to the knife. The roller K is mounted in the frame L, M to rotate in two places at right-angles, about the axes k, m.

column12: ELEVATOR SHUTTLE SYSTEM
column13: A multi-hoistway shuttle system in which elevator cabs (A, B, C, D, E) are transported between levels. A plurality of hoistways are arranged adjacent one another and overlap, except the upper and lower hoistways. The cabs (A, B, C, D, E) are loaded at a first level into elevator cars, each of which has a plurality of decks and travels vertically in a hoistway. At the top or bottom of each hoistway a car which has reached the top of a lower hoistway and a car which has reached the bottom of an adjacent upper hoistway are situated side by side. The cabs are exchanged by moving them horizontally into the adjacent car. The car containing the new cab is then transported vertically and the cab inside the car continues its journey up or down until the desired level is reached. In the system described there are N cabs for each hoistway plus N for each level, 2N landings at each level and 3N decks on each car. This system allows more efficient transport of passengers while requiring less hoistways and therefore less space in a building.
column15: SPANER MICHAEL A;;BARKER FREDERICK H

column12: Improvements in Internal Combustion Engines.
column13: 22,622. Hill, F. B., and Best, W. G. Oct. 7. Jet-wheels; regulating; reversing; working- fluid supply. - Relates to internal - combustion engines of the type comprising one or more units each consisting of a pair of cylinders, partly filled with water, which are provided at their upper ends with admission and exhaust valves and ignition devices, and communicate with one another at their lower ends through a casing provided with a turbine from the shaft of which power is taken off. The principal feature of the invention is that the circuits of the ignition devices are made and broken by the rise and fall of the water in the cylinders, the water coming into direct contact with an insulated contact forming part of each ignition circuit. In the arrangement shown in Fig. 1, the turbine casing 10 and cylinders 1, 1<1> are filled with water from a pipe 32 up to the level of the cocks 35, and at starting, combustible mixture is drawn into both cylinders by means of a suction pump connected to the pipe 24. Upon ignition of the mixture in, say, the cylinder 1<1> by the closing of a switch, the water is driven past the turbine 3 into the cylinder 1, compressing the charge therein. As soon as the water comes into contact with the igniting- device 21, a spark is produced at the plug 20 and ignition occurs in the cylinder 1, driving the water back through the turbine 3 to the cylinder 1'. The rush of water past the plate 15 opens the exhaust valve 13, but as soon as the water passes below the level of the plate, the exhaust valve closes under the action of the spring 16 and fresh combustible charge is sucked in through an admission valve (not shown). A fresh explosion then occurs in the cylinder 1<1>, and the action of the apparatus becomes continuous and automatic. A by-pass connecting the lower ends of the two cylinders may be opened to facilitate starting. In a modification. the turbine 3 may be mounted in a casing through which the water flows in one direction only, as shown in Figs. 5 and 6, valves 45, 46 being fitted in the chambers 42, 41 beneath the cylinders 1, 1<1> to direct the flow in the proper direction. In this case, the by-pass valve 49 may be fitted between the chambers 41, 42 and may serve for regulating the volume of liquid flowing through the turbine as well as for starting. Reversal may be effected by a separate turbine wheel mounted in the shaft 4 and a valve for diverting the stream of liquid through it. The water may be cooled by means of a condenser through which a portion of the water may be diverted at every stroke. The exhaust valves may be operated electrically by means of electro-magnets inserted in circuits which are made and broken at the required times by the rise and fall of the water in the cylinders of the engine.

Tiles, special shapes of.-A continuous regenerator for gaseous-fuel retort furnaces is built up of refractory tiles of special shape arranged to form baffled passages for air and combustion products adjacent one another, the tiles being so shaped and arranged that leakage between the air and gas passages is prevented. Figs. 1 and 2 show two views of a tile, and Fig. 5 shows the manner of arranging the tiles to form the regenerator. Each tile a is provided with an overhanging portion b, which abuts against a corresponding portion on another tile to form the floor and roof of two superposed passages. Recesses c are provided to receive the lower ends of the superposed tiles, and recesses j and projections i in the edges of the tiles engage with corresponding projections and recesses in adjacent tiles. Ribs d are provided on the faces of the tiles, and the inner top edge of each tile is splayed to form a channel g between adjacent tiles to receive a filling of fire-clay, putty, &c. To prevent leakage through the side joints, the joints of one vertical row of passages are stepped down below the joints of an adjacent row, as shown at k, Fig. 5.

column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a safety device 16 capable of stopping the movement of an elevator car in the overspeed condition on a guide rail 14 made of a non-ferrous material. SOLUTION: This safety device 16 includes one or more wedges 20 formed of a rigid material, and one surface of these wedges is provided with a friction surface 24 to be brought in contact with a surface of a guide rail 14 when the overspeed condition is generated, and other surface thereof is provided with a bearing surface 22 to be pushed to a slide or a roller member 30. When the overspeed condition is generated, the wedge is pulled to be brought in contact with the slide or the roller member, and the slide or the roller member gives the force in the horizontal direction to the wedge, and pushes the wedge for a contact with the guide rail 14, and the braking operation is obtained at this contact position. The wedge is desirably arranged in a pair with an opposite surface of each guide rail 14.

column12: Improvements in Apparatus for Dyeing, Mordanting, or Washing Fibrous Materials.
column13: 14,125. Dargue, W., Dargue, F. L., and Barker, H. June 25. Dyeing ; washing.-In a dyeing, mordanting, or washing machine in which hanks are traversed vertically through the dye &c. liquor on carriers slung from rollers on a lifter-frame above the vat, means are provided for interlocking the controlling-levers of the gears which rotate the rollers and lift their frame, for locking the lever of the lifting-gear until the rollers are free to move into or out of their driving-sockets, and for automatically stopping the lifting-gear and the gear which traverses the frame and rollers away from the vat. Reference is made to Specification No. 7060, A.D. 1903. The hank carriers each consist of upper and lower rollers 47, 52, Fig. 12, connected by loose brackets 48, 51 and jointed arms 49, 50. The joints of the arms 49, 50 are knuckled to cause the arms to fold inwards when the roller 52 is raised towards the roller 47 to receive the hanks, The hanks are stretched by the weight of sand &c. contained in the hollow roller 52, and are prevented from lapping round the rollers by V-shaped guards 53, 54 of thin metal &c. attached to the brackets 48, 51. When in position above the vat, the rollers 47 at one end 14', Fig. 6, engage in sockets 13 on spindles 12, Figs. 1, 3, and 6, which are driven from worms 11. These worms are driven from a main shaft 1 through gearing controlled by a lever 8 and a clutch-rod within the shaft 1. Drums 5, 7 carrying the lifting and traversing ropes of the lifter-frame are similarly driven from shafts 3, 6 fitted with internal clutch-rods controlled by levers 9, 10. In the arrangements for interlocking the levers 8, 9 and for locking the lifting-gear lever 9, a box or guide 23 on the frame 16 is formed with guide-ways for vertical and horizontal bolts 26, 20 connected to the levers 8, 9. These ways overlap, and the bolts are cut away in rectangular notches, so that both are free to move when both levers 8, 9 are in their vertical or " off" positions ; movement of either lever 8 or 9 locks the other. The bolt 20 also carries two teeth 21, 22, which prevent it from being moved until a notched disc 15', driven synchronously with the wheels 2 and sockets 13 by a wheel 15 and one of the worms 11. presents its notches 18, 19 to the teeth 21, 22. This occurs when the sockets 13 are in position to receive or free the roller-heads 14<1>. The stopping-mechanism of the lifting-gear consists of a worm 27, Fig. 10, turning with the shaft 3 and driving a shaft 29 which carries a worm.wheel 28, a single-toothed wheel 31, and a locking-plate 35. The wheel 31 drives a loose wheel 32 on a stud 33, and the plate 35 co-operates with a stopplate 36 to lock the wheel 32 except while the tooth 31<1> is acting. When the gear has performed a predetermined number of revolutions, the wheels 31, 32 are stopped by a piece 34 on the wheel 32, and the wheel 31 then acts as a rack to slide the worm 27 along the shaft 3, carrying the clutch rod 3<1> with it until the clutch is in the "off" position. Two or more stops 34 may be provided on the wheel 32, and two or more teeth 31<1> on the wheel 31, according to the arrangements of the driving- gear. A similar arrangement is provided for stopping the rotation of the shaft 6 which drives the traversing-mechanism.

column13: 22,965. Hill, F. B., and Westwood, G. J. W. Oct. 17. [Cognate Application No. 2874, A.D. 1908, dated Feb. 8.] Carburetting.-A carburetting-plant comprises a pumping-bell automatically operated by water pressure, a carburettor in which air is drawn through or over the surface of hydrocarbon, and a holder into which the carburetted air is forced, the whole being preferably arranged in a water tank, and all the joints being preferably formed by liquid seals. The bell b is raised by water supplied through a pipe 12, the water supply being controlled by tappets 31, 32. Air is thereby sucked in through a valve f, pipes g, j, condensing chamber i, pipes m, n, and a submerged perforated hood q connected to a float p, and the carburetted air is drawn into the bell b through a valve w, cylinder y, and telescopic pipe 7. The bell b falls by gravity and forces the gas back through the pipe 7, cylinder y, valve 3, and telescopic pipe 14 into the gas holder c, which it leaves by a pipe 18. The ends of the pipes 7, 14, 18 are provided with mixing boxes 7<a>. The exhaust water from the cylinder 8 passes into the tank d, which is provided with an overflow 33 and a heating-coil 34. The height of the tube n in the chamber r serves to indicate the level of hydrocarbon in the carburettor a. The composition of the gas may be adjusted by admitting a subsidiary air supply through a graduated valve on a branch pipe leading into the pipe 7. In a modification the air may be drawn from the chamber i through pipes 41, Fig. 5, opening into nozzles 44, the air thus drawing in vapour from the surface of the liquid through the openings 52. Parts of the apparatus, such as the bell b, may be duplicated. Nozzles of other shapes than those shown may be employed, and in some cases the hydrocarbon is drawn or injected into a mixing-chamber by the air in the form of a spray or mist which becomes absorbed by the air.

column13: An elevator system comprises a plurality of low rise elevators providing service between a lobby floor and the highest floor of a low rise in the building, high rise elevators providing express service between a lobby floor and the lowest floor of a high rise in the building as well as providing service to floors between the lowest floor of the high rise and the highest floor of the high rise, and a plurality of high-only elevators which provide service only to floors between the lowest floor of the high rise and the highest floor of the high rise, having no express zone to extend service downward to the lobby. column12: Improvements in Apparatus for Cutting Cloth upon the Bias.
column13: 23,432. Mitchell, C. F., Barker, J. L., and Whittaker, J. Oct. 24. Cutting tubes of cylindrical form &c. transversely to their length.-In apparatus for cutting tubular cloth helically into long lengths of cloth upon the bias, as described in Specification 10,683/07, the cloth is conveyed to the drawing-off rollers B, C from the stationary cylinder A by a single endless spiked chain or inextensible band G. This chain &c. may be arranged to engage the severed cloth at its edges or medially, or a separate chain may be used for each purpose. A chain of the pattern shown in Fig. 10 is preferably employed, having spikes g on alternate vertical links. This chain is arranged to travel in a groove H with the spikes g projecting in a groove between bars h<1> which serve to keep the material on the spikes. The groove H may be provided with antifriction rollers. The cloth is delivered to the cylinder A by rollers p, Fig. 7, from a beam R carried by a rotary frame P. The front of this frame is of annular form, and is fitted with rollers p<1> engaging a fixed annular cradle R'. The rollers p are rotated through gearing from pinions s which rotate on a fixed wheel s' when the frame P is rotated. The under portion of the cylinder A may be cut away in the vicinity of the chain groove thereby enabling the drawing-off roller B to be placed nearer to the cylinder. The cloth is pressed on the spiked chain immediately before it reaches the cutter by a reciprocating brush &c. E, and a resilient or screw-operated brush or plate may be used to remove creases from the cloth before severance. Vertical-cutter type for cutting sheet material in direction of feed.-The severed strip of cloth may be subdivided into smaller strips by a series of adjustable disk cutters K', Fig. 9, coacting with grooves in the drawing-off rollers B. Alternatively, the roller B may be replaced by a series of narrow drums with the cutters working between them. The grooves &c. are kept clean by fingers N engaging therewith, and an adjustable bar M presses the cloth on the roller B during the cutting operation. An extension of the cutter spindle K serves to accommodate any cutters not immediately required.

[Addition to 23,432/11.] Cutting cylinders, tubes, &c. transversely to their length.-The single inextensible chain &c. described in the parent Specification for drawing the fabric over the cylinder is replaced by upper and lower coacting bands or the like. The upper band may be replaced by two bands. The bands B, C may be of the shape shown in Fig. 4 and be guided and driven by correspondingly-shaped pulleys b<1>. In a modification, the bands B, C, Fig. 8, or equivalent gripper blocks c, f, Fig. 11, are carried by chains E, F, respectively, guided in slotted races G', G. In another modification, the band B, Fig. 4, may be replaced by a wire rope B<5>, Fig. 6, adapted to engage a groove c in a lower chain-supported band C. In all these constructions, the pressure of the upper band &c. on the lower is controlled by a suitable screw or spring adjustment, and the gripping-surfaces of the bands are preferably indented or corrugated. In a modification, short coacting bands may be employed in combination with grippers or clips of the type used in stentering machines. To ensure that the cloth a, Fig. 13, is delivered to the cylinder A without creasing, a plate k is inserted in the cloth between the feed - rollers p. This plate k is mounted loosely on a screw or rod l and adapted to rotate with the frame carrying the feed-rollers.

column12: ELEVATOR HOISTWAY AND ELEVATOR DEVICE
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide guide rails made of a non-ferrous material and an elevator guide device. SOLUTION: Guide rails 12 are integrally formed with the structure of a hoistway 10, and desirably include concrete. Plural air cushions are provided in an elevator car adjacent to the concrete rails 12, and when the elevator car moves in the vertical direction, these air cushions inject the air flow to at least one, desirably all of the surfaces of the rails 12 and at least the rail 12 of the car to control so that the energizing force is generated between each rail 12 and the car. Air is supplied by a fan or other supply source. The car is positioned at the center position of each hoistway by the air flow injected to each surface, and the smooth and quiet elevating operation is thereby provided.

column12: METHOD FOR SEPARATION OF DEXTRANS
column13: The invention described and claimed in the specification is a new method for separation of a fluid mixture of dextrans of differing molecular weights into two fractions, which comprises(a) passing said mixture into chromatographic apparatus which comprises a plurality of compartments which contain an appropriate packing material, valve-containing conduits interconnecting the compartments to provide a closed loop column, at least one additional valve controlled fluid inlet and at least one additional valve controlled fluit outlet for each compartment, and means for sequential operation of the valves, and(b) operating the valves sequentially such that each compartment undergoes, and at any one time there is at least one compartment undergoing, the following operations: (i) being fed with the fluid mixture to be separated,(ii) being fed with a carrier fluid,(iii) having carrier fluid and any entrained faster moving components of the fluid mixture removed therefrom, and (iv) being isolated and treated to remove any slower moving components of the fluid mixture; the compartment being fed with fluid mixture to be separated being a compartment through which the carrier fluid passes.

Pigmented polyamides are prepared by polymerizing a mixture of 90 to 99À5 wt per cent hexamethylenediammonium adipate and 0À5 to 10 wt. per cent of caprolactam in the presence of an organic pigment. Specified pigments are quinacridone, phthalocyanine and perylene pigments, e.g. copper phthalocyanine or the bis- N,N<SP>1</SP>-(3<SP>1</SP>,5<SP>1</SP>-dimethylphenyl) imide of perylene- 3,4,9,10-tetracarboxylic acid. Inorganic pigments, e.g. TiO 2 , carbon black, cadmium sulphide or selenide, or iron oxide, may also be present and a viscosity stabilizer, e.g. acetic acid, may be employed.

column12: Improved process for the manufacture of azo dyes
column13: Sulphamic acids of formula <FORM:0892323/IV (b)/1> wherein A is an arylene radical which may be substituted other than by sulphonic acid groups, R is a hydrogen atom or an alkyl radical with 1-4 carbon atoms which may be further substituted and Z is a heterocyclic ring attached to the -NR- group through a carbon atom of an <FORM:0892323/IV (b)/2> group which is present in the heterocyclic ring are obtained by treating a compound of formula <FORM:0892323/IV (b)/3> with a chlorinated heterocyclic compound Z-Cl. They are used in the preparation of azo dyes (see Group IV (c)). In Examples (1) 4-amino-phenylsulphamic acid is reacted with 2 : 4 : 6-trichloropyrimidine in aqueous ethanol in the presence of sodium carbonate to give the sodium salt of 4-(dichloropyrimidylamino) phenylsulphamic acid; (2) an aqueous solution of 4-41 : 61-dichloro-11 : 31 : 51-triazin-21-ylamino) phenylsulphamic acid sodium salt obtained by the process of (1) but using cyanuric chloride is further reacted with an alkaline solution of 2-mercapto-benzthiazole to give the sodium salt of 4 - [41 - chloro - 61 - (benzthiazol - 211 - ylthio) - 11 : 31 : 51-triazin-21-ylamino]-phenylsulphamic acid. Similar compounds are prepared in aqueous solution in further examples. 2 - Methoxy-4-amino-5 - methylphenylsulphamic acid is prepared by treating 2-methoxy-4-nitro-5-methylaniline with chlorosulphonic acid in the presence of dimethylaniline and reducing the nitro group. 4 - N - methylamino - phenylsulphamic acid is prepared by reducing N-methyl-4-nitroacetanilide with sodium bisulphite followed by alkaline saponification of the N-acetyl group. Specification 838,337 is referred to.ALSO:Azo dyes of formula <FORM:0892323/IV (c)/1> wherein A is an arylene radical which may contain substituents other than a sulphonic acid group, B is the residue of a coupling component which may contain an arylazo group, R is a hydrogen atom or an alkyl radical with 1-4 carbon atoms which may be further substituted and Z is a heterocyclic ring which is attached to the -NR- group through the carbon atom of a <FORM:0892323/IV (c)/2> group which is present in the heterocyclic ring, are prepared by diazotising a sulphamic acid of formula <FORM:0892323/IV (c)/3> or a metal salt thereof (see Group IV(b)), and coupling the diazo compound so obtained with a coupling component B-H. The heterocyclic ring Z is preferably a mono- or di-halo-triazine residue. In Examples: (1) an aqueous solution of 4 - [41 - chloro - 61 - di(b - hydroxyethyl)amino - 11 : 31 : 51 - triazin - 21 - ylamino] phenylsulphamic acid is treated with sodium nitrite solution and p hydrochloric acid and the diazo compound obtained is coupled with p-cresol; (2) 4-(41 : 61 - dichloro - 11 : 31 : 51 - triazin - 21 - yl amino) - phenyl sulphamic acid is treated as in (1) and the diazo compound coupled with 1 - (21 - sulphophenylazo) - 2 - amino - 5 - naphthol - 7 - sulphonic acid. Many further examples are specified. Specification 838,337 is referred to.

column12: PRESSURE SENSOR
column13: A sensor suitable for measuring the pressure applied by a bandage, the sensor being in the form of an elongate strip having a plurality of pads arranged along its length, wherein the sensor includes a connection to each pad, whereby the pressure applied to each pad can be determined independently, wherein each pad is inflatable to form an expanded pad protruding above the surface of the strip, and deflatable so that it does not impede removal of the sensor from the bandage. Such a sensor is primarily intended for single use, i.e. is disposable.

column12: Horizontal transfer of elevator cab between elevator frame and landing bogey
column13: An elevator system comprises an elevator frame 43 vertically movable in a hoistway 43H, a cab 13 mounted on a wheeled carriage 15 and a wheeled bogey 28 adapted to move along tracks 29 on a landing 36. A pair of rails 40 are mounted on the elevator frame to extend substantially across the hoistway, the rails spaced to cooperate with the wheeled carriage. A similar pair of rails 26 having the same spacing are mounted on the bogey. The wheeled carriage has a pair of wheels 20 at each corner. The ends of the rails are scarfed(127, Fig. 2; 132, Fig. 3) in a complementary fashion so as to provide a temporary half-lap joint between the rails of the bogey 26 and the rails of the elevator frame 40 when the two are aligned adjacent one another. This provides a continuous surface for the wheeled carriage to travel over, the spacing between the wheels 16, 17 of each pair of wheels being such that one or other of the wheels will be on a full section of rail at all times. Additional preferred features are urethane coated wheels, tapers at the ends of the rails and guide rollers (86-89, Fig. 4) on the carriage having vertical axes adapted to roll against an inside vertical face of each rail.

column12: Wall thermostat and the like
column13: Apparatus is provided for a wall mounted thermostat to accept and convert manually generated instructions to binary encoded electronic impulses to control ambient air conditions in the environment in which the thermostat is located. The parameters of operation include a building heating control which reduces the desired ambient temperature at night, beginning at a prescribed time and returning to a higher daytime level at a different prescribed time. The system may also adjust desired temperature depending upon humidity conditions and alter the timing of heating and air conditioning control by predicting when a desired temperature will be reached in order to avoid overshoot. The system includes a liquid crystal or light emitting diode display and communicates with a power source and with heating and air conditioning switches such as relays or contactors.

column12: DUCT WITH SHAPE MEMORY MATERIAL, AND INSTALLATION METHOD
column13: Ducting and/or duct couplings can be formed from shape memory polymer material, with the material for example being additively manufactured. The use of shape memory polymer material for one or more of the duct portions may allow for easier installation of the ducting, for example allowing the ducting to be warped and/or bent to fit into or through places that are hard to reach or hard to maneuver through, with the ducting then heated to cause it to return to a predetermined memory shape. The coupling of duct portions together may be accomplished by the duct portions including a shape memory polymer material, with for example ends of the duct portions fitted together, and then heated to use a shape memory property of the material to effect coupling. Heating of the shape memory polymer material also softens the material, allowing it to move to a previously set shape.

column12: Elevator shuttle with auxiliary elevators at terminals
column13: Elevator cabs A-C move upwardly through three or more contiguous overlapping hoistways 38-40 in the upper decks of double deck car frames 41-43, and move downwardly through the hoistways in the lower decks (or vice versa). To switch between decks, the cabs are offloaded from the hoistways into auxiliary elevators 50, 51 at the terminal ends of the shuttle, and are moved to be adjacent to the other deck by the auxiliary elevator and loaded thereon for the trip in the opposite direction. A second embodiment has additional auxiliary elevators 64, 65 and additional cabs D, E so that loading and unloading of passengers do not delay movement of the cabs in the hoistways.
column15: SALMON JOHN K;;BITTAR JOSEPH;;COONEY ANTHONY;;MCCARTHY RICHARD C;;BARKER FREDERICK H

column12: LEARNING ROAD NAVIGATION PATHS BASED ON AGGREGATE DRIVER BEHAVIOR
column13: Techniques are described for generating and using information regarding road traffic in various ways, including by obtaining and analyzing road traffic information regarding actual behavior of drivers of vehicles on a network of roads. Obtained actual driver behavior information may in some situations be analyzed to identify decision point locations at which drivers face choices corresponding to possible alternative routes through the network of roads (e.g., intersections, highway exits and/or entrances, etc.), as well as to track the actual use by drivers of particular paths between particular decision points in order to determine preferred compound links between those decision point locations. The identified and determined information from the analysis may then be used in various manners, including in some situations to assist in determining particular recommended or preferred routes of vehicles through the network of roads based at least in part on actual driver behavior information.

column12: COMPOUND OVERNIGHT BANK RATE ACCRUAL FUTURES CONTRACT AND COMPUTATION OF VARIATION MARGIN THEREFORE
column13: The disclosed embodiments relate to an exchange-traded futures contract, guaranteed by a clearing house, and characterized by an embedded price dynamic comprising a compound accrual of a periodic interest rate up to a date on which trading therein is terminated, as specified in the futures contract terms and conditions. A trader may be allowed and/or enabled to take a position in a futures contract with respect to an interest bearing underlier with a variable interest rate and, thereby, minimize the number of transactions and attendant costs with respect to monitoring and correcting for divergences between the futures position and the notional interest rate swap exposure for which the futures position is intended to serve as a proxy. Variation margin for the position is computed based on an underlying reference interest rate as opposed to being computed solely on the basis of the end-of-business day price of the futures contract.

column12: percursos de navegação para aprendizado de estradas com base em comportamento agregado de motorista
column13: percursos de navegação para aprendizado de estrada com base em comportamento agregado de motorista. técnicas são descritas para a geração e utilização de informação referente ao tráfego de estrada de várias formas, incluindo pela obtenção e análise de informação de tráfego rodoviário referente ao comportamento real de motorista de veículos em uma rede de estradas. a informação comportamental de motorista real obtida pode, em algumas situações, ser analisada para identifica as localizações de ponto de decisão nas quais os motoristas se deparam com escolhas correspondentes a possíveis rotas alternativas através da rede de estradas (por exemplo, interseções, saídas de vias expressas e/ou entradas, etc.), além de rastrear o uso real pelos motoristas de percuros particulares entre os pontos de decisão particulares a fim de determinar as conexões compostas preferidas entre essas localizações de ponto de decisão. a informação identificada e determinada da análise pode então ser utilizada de várias formas, incluindo, em algumas situações, auxiliar na determinação de rotas de veículos recomendadas ou preferidas através da rede de estradas com base pelo menos em parte na informação comportamental de motorista real.

column12: Learning road navigation paths based on aggregate driver behavior
column13: Techniques are described for generating and using information regarding road traffic in various ways, including by obtaining and analyzing road traffic information regarding actual behavior of drivers of vehicles on a network of roads. Obtained actual driver behavior information may in some situations be analyzed to identify decision point locations at which drivers face choices corresponding to possible alternative routes through the network of roads (e.g., intersections, highway exits and/or entrances, etc.), as well as to track the actual use by drivers of particular paths between particular decision points in order to determine preferred compound links between those decision point locations. The identified and determined information from the analysis may then be used in various manners, including in some situations to assist in determining particular recommended or preferred routes of vehicles through the network of roads based at least in part on actual driver behavior information.

column12: LOGIC CONTROLLED DIGITAL WALL THERMOSTAT
column13: WALL THERMOSTAT AND THE LIKE DOCKET NO. 2905-S Apparatus is provided for a wall mounted thermostat to accept and convert manually generated instructions to binary encoded electronic impulses to control ambient air conditions in the environment in which the thermostat is located. The parameters of operation include a building heating control which reduces the desired ambient temperature at night, beginning at a prescribed time and returning to a higher daytime level at a different prescribed time. The system may also adjust desired temperature depending upon humidity conditions and alter the timing of heating and air conditioning control by predicting when a desired temperature will be reached in order to avoid overshoot. The system includes a liquid crystal or light emitting diode display and communicates with a power source and with heating and air conditioning switches such as relays or contactors.

column12: Multiple trade matching algorithms
column13: MULTIPLE TRADE MATCHING ALGORITHMS The disclosed embodiments relate to systems and methods which natch/allocate an incoming order to trade with "resting," i.e, previously received but not yet matched, orders, recognizing that the algorithm or rules by which the incoming order is matched iay affect the operation of the market for the financial product being traded. In particular, the disclosed embodiments relate to an adaptive match engine (106) which draws upon different matching algorithms, e.g. the rules which dictate how a given order should be allocated among qualifying resting orders, depending upon market conditions, to improve the operation of the market. Thereby, by conditionally switching among matching algorithms within the same financial product, as will be described, the disclosed match engine (106) automatically adapts to the changing market conditions of a financial product, e.g. a liinited life product, in a non-preferential manner, maintaining fair order allocation while improving market liquidity, e.g., over the life of the product. 7523259_1 '4 V Om~ 31 too

column12: Combustion chamber for a gas turbine engine
column13: A combustion chamber for a gas turbine engine comprising at least one Helmholtz resonator having a resonator cavity and a resonator neck in flow communication with the interior of the combustion chamber. The cavity extends around at least part of the neck and is spaced apart therefrom to define a cooling chamber therebetween. The cooling chamber allows the neck and the cavity to be cooled with a flow of cooling air. The sunken neck allows the resonator to be located within enclosures with minimal volume without compromising on the damping properties afforded.

column12: Improvements in or relating to fastener inserting machines
column13: 1,018,591. Riveting. BRITISH UNITED SHOE MACHINERY CO. Ltd. Sept. 19, 1962 [Sept. 21, 1961], Nos. 33746/61 and 24796/62. Heading B3U. A fastener inserting machine comprises a reciprocable die holder, a fastener support comprising jaws urged towards one another, reciprocable in the same direction as the die holder and arranged to support in the path of a die carried by the die holder a fastener to be inserted, driving means for effecting reciprocation of the die holder and fastener support and actuating means interconnecting the die holder and fastener support for effecting relative movement therebetween, whereby the die carried by the die holder is caused to engage a fastener supported by the jaws and thereafter the jaws are opened to release the fastener prior to its insertion into the workpiece. Construction.-The machine comprises a frame 10 in which is mounted a lower die 14 and a reciprocating driver bar 30 which carries an upper die 32 which has a spring-pressed central nipple pin. The driver bar 30 is connected to an eccentric pin 52 on the shaft 40 which is driven through a treadle-operated one-revolution clutch. In front of the driver bar 30 is mounted a carrier 56 which reciprocates with the driver bar but also has movement relative to the bar. This movement is produced by a cam-operated lever 60, Figs. 2 and 4 (not shown), and a three-armed lever 64. The lever 64 is pivoted at 63 to a projecting ear 62 on the driver bar and has a roller 66 at one end which runs in a slot 68 in the carrier 56. Another arm carries a roller 74 which is maintained, by a spring 70, in contact with a flat vertical face 76 of the lever 60. The lever 60 is pivoted at 78 and has a roller 80 which runs on a cam 82, driven from the shaft 40 by bevel gears 88 and 90. At the lower end of the carrier 56 a pair of spring- closed jaws 100 are pivoted on pins 102, 104, Fig. 6 (not shown), the jaws have shoulders which provide support for the flange of an eyelet E. The jaws are opened by two pins 110 mounted on the driver bar which engage cam faces 112 on the jaws. Feeding eyelets.-A hopper 124 is mounted on three inclined tangentially arranged springs and is vibrated by an electromagnet 132. There is a bevel around the periphery of the floor and eyelets ride along the wall 129, Figs. 10 and 12 (not shown), with their flanges in the groove, up an inclined face 138 to a tangential exit channel 144. Eyelets 150 which are incorrectly orientated are deflected by a block 146, 154 to the interior of the hopper. Those which enter the channel 144 pass into a raceway 122 and travel down to a feed disc 170, Fig. 3 (not shown), mounted on a vertical spindle and intermittently rotated by a Geneva mechanism 176, 178 driven from the shaft 86 which carries the bevel gear 88. Eyelets are transferred from the disc 170 to the carrier 56 by two thin spring fingers 182 which engage the parts of the eyelet projecting above and below the feed disc. The fingers are mounted on an arm 184 secured to a vertical shaft 186. A second arm 188 also secured to the shaft is connected by a link 190 to a lever 194 which is pivoted at 197 and carries a roller 202 which is maintained, by a spring 198, in contact with a cam 204 also mounted on the shaft 86. Operation.-With a workpiece positioned over the lower die 14 the clutch is tripped and the driver bar 30 and carrier 56 descend together with the lever 60 swinging through a small angle so that the driver advances relative to the carrier and the nipple pin enters the eyelet. Relative movement between the driver bar and carrier then ceases until the latter part of the stroke is reached when the driver bar again advances and opens the jaws 100, thereafter the carrier remains stationary while the upper die sets the eyelet. In a modification to the hopper the raceway instead of being rigidly connected to the frame of the machine and spaced from the hopper by a sufficient amount to allow for the vibration of the hopper, is connected to the hopper or the hopper mounting through a resilient coupling.

column12: SIDE BRUSH WITH BRISTLES AT DIFFERENT LENGTHS AND/OR ANGLES FOR USE IN A ROBOT CLEANER AND SIDE BRUSH DEFLECTORS
column13: A robot cleaner including a body, a driven wheel, and a side brush coupled to the body. The side brush includes a hub configured to rotate about a pivot axis and a plurality of bristles. Some bristles may form a first angle with the pivot axis and others form a second angle with the pivot axis which is larger than the first angle. Some bristles may have a first bristle length and others have a second bristle length which is larger than the first bristle length. The robot cleaner may include a side brush deflector to deflect debris propelled by the side brush towards the vacuum inlet. column12: Transferring freight or passenger cabs between moving bogies
column13: Cabs, such as passenger and freight cabs, are transferred from one horizontal transport bogie that is moving along a track to another horizontal transport bogie moving at the same speed on an adjacent track. The cab may be transferred from one train or shuttle of moving bogies to another train of moving bogies, or may be transferred from a train of moving bogies to an auxiliary shuttle or bogie on a siding so as to permit the cab to be brought to a stop, either to allow transfer of passengers, to be moved into the car frame of an adjacent elevator for vertical transport within the building, or to simply await the coming of another train, traveling in either the same or in opposite direction, to which the cab may then be transferred.

column12: Water-activatable polymers and printable constructions
column13: Water dispersible, hydrophilic, repulpable, water-activatable, acrylic polymers are provided. The polymers are non-tacky when dry, but become tacky when wet, and exhibit high peel strength on a variety of substrates. The polymers comprise an acrylic-based polymer prepared by emulsion polymerization of 40 to 70% by weight of one or more alkyl acrylates, the alkyl group of which has from 4 to 8 carbon atoms; 10 to 20% by weight of methacrylate; 2 to 15% by weight of vinyl acetate; and 10 to 25 percent by weight of methacrylic acid and/or acrylic acid; and a positive amount up to about 30% by weight of methyl methacrylate. Some embodiments also include a short chain hydroxyalkyl methacrylate. Also provided are ink jet-imprintable, water-activatable constructions comprising a layer of water-activatable polymer, coated on a release liner or other surface. Optionally, a water-resistant transparent film layer is disposed between the polymer and release liner or used in place of the release liner. The constructions are suitable for use in ink jet printers and can be used to transfer an image to a substrate.

column12: SIDE BRUSH WITH BRISTLES AT DIFFERENT LENGTHS AND/OR ANGLES FOR USE IN A ROBOT CLEANER AND SIDE BRUSH DEFLECTORS
column13: A robot cleaner including a body, a driven wheel, and a side brush coupled to the body. The side brush includes a hub configured to rotate about a pivot axis and a plurality of bristles. Some bristles may form a first angle with the pivot axis and others form a second angle with the pivot axis which is larger than the first angle. Some bristles may have a first bristle length and others have a second bristle length which is larger than the first bristle length. The robot cleaner may include a side brush deflector to deflect debris propelled by the side brush towards the vacuum inlet. The side brush deflector includes a plurality of deflector bristles extending downwardly from a floor facing surface of the robot cleaner towards a floor such that some of the bristles pass through or underneath a portion of the deflector bristles.

column12: ADHESIVE IMAGE TRANSFER TECHNIQUE COMPRISING PRINTING AN INK JET IMAGE ON A DETACKIFIED ADHESIVE LAYER, ACTIVATING THE LAYER AND ADHERING THE IMAGE SHEET AND POLYMERS THEREFOR
column13: An image transfer assembly (12) receives an image printed from an ink jet printer. The assembly (12) provides a device to transfer the printed image onto an image-receiving surface. The assembly (12) has a flexible substrate (16) on one side, and an upper surface (20) on the other side that is substantially permeable to ink jet printer ink and that is non-tacky prior to printing. The assembly (12) has an adhesive or polymer layer (14) in between the upper surface (20) and the flexible substrate (16). After printing with a water-based ink jet printer ink, the user may apply the assembly (12) to a substrate, such as a window or other surface, and remove the flexible substrate (16), thereby leaving the layer (14) that bears the image on the substrate. In one of several alternative embodiments, the layer (14) is divided into discrete zones that are separated from one another along boundaries.

column12: Passenger transfer, double deck, multi-elevator shuttle system
column13: An elevator shuttle system for moving passengers between landings at two levels of a building, comprising: a plurality of overlapping elevator hoistways, each hoistway except for the highest hoistway in the system having its high end aligned with the high end of another, corresponding one of the hoistways at a transfer landing, and each hoistway except for the lowest hoistway in the system having its low end aligned with the high end of another, corresponding one of the hoistways, the high end of the highest hoistway being aligned with a landing at a top level of the system high in the building and the low end of the lowest elevator being aligned with a landing at a bottom level of the system low in the building; a plurality of double deck elevator cars, each vertically moveable in a related one of the hoistways, each deck comprising a passenger compartment, each compartment comprising a permanent part of the car, one above the other, each of the cars having doors operable at each deck facing the corresponding hoistway, the cars of the highest hoistway and of the lowest hoistway having doors facing the corresponding one of the landings, each hoistway separated from a corresponding hoistway by a pair of sills aligned with the decks; and signal processing means for setting the direction of and initiating each run of the cars so that at the end of each run, each car is either aligned with one of the landings or aligned with the car of the corresponding hoistway, and for opening all of the doors of all of the cars at the end of each run so that passengers can walk from the upper deck of one car to the upper deck of another car and from the lower deck of the other car to the lower deck of the one car, or alternatively, from the upper deck of the one car to the upper deck of one of the landings and from the lower deck of the one landing to the lower deck of the one car.

column12: Method and apparatus of stud array upstand setting
column13: An apparatus and method for setting the upstand height of the studs of an array of studs used to form antenna panels is disclosed. The apparatus includes a transducer beam having a row of spaced-apart distance transducers. The apparatus also includes an actuator beam having a row of spaced rotary actuators. The actuators rotate the threaded studs to raise or lower the studs until the corresponding transducer indicates that the stud has achieved an intended height. Also disclosed is a method using an array of laser diodes, rather than the transducer beam, arranged at one end of the base plate and an array of photo diodes at the opposite end. The output of the diodes indicates the height of the studs.

column12: Devices and methods for eliminating termite colonies
column13: This invention relates to devices, kits, and methods for eliminating termite colonies. The kits, devices, and methods employ a termiticidal bait matrix containing a) a termiticide selected such that the termiticide causes death to about 50 to about 100% of termites within about 24 to about 84 days after the termites begin to ingest the termiticide or the bait matrix comprising the termiticide,b) a cellulose containing material, andc) water. The termiticidal bait matrix can be used in a bait station installed in the ground. The kits are suitable to be used by consumers in their homes.

column12: PUMPING SYSTEM
column13: To select a designated bottle in a sampler, the distributor is calibrated as to position and the outlet of the distributor arm is moved over the desired bottle by counting changes in incremental angular movement of the distributor arm until it is over the bottle. The position of the distributor arm is recorded in memory. To calibrate the distributor, the arm is rotated against a stop member in a first direction, then in a second direction and the overrun of in excess of 360 degrees of the motion of the distributor arm is determined and corrected. A series of random numbers is generated for depositing of samples, the distributor is moved at designated times over the bottles in a random order to deposit a sample and the ordering of bottles is recorded. The rollers of a peristaltic pump are supported to prevent said rollers from compressing said tube more than the thickness of the walls of the tube. A functional module for a bubbler or pH probe or ultrasonic level detector may be connected to the housing.

column12: Fail-safe movement of elevator cabs between car frames and landings
column13: A first slidable auxiliary pinion (58a) on the bottom of a horizontally moveable elevator cab A (FIGS. 2-6) disposed on a car frame (14) or a landing is moved out from under the cab toward another car frame (13) or landing by means of a motorized pinion (56) until it engages a motorized pinion (57) on the adjacent car frame (13) or landing, which then pulls the auxiliary pinion and the entire cab toward the other car frame or landing until a main rack (45) fixed to the bottom of the cab engages a motorized pinion (34) on the other car frame (13) or landing, which pinion then pulls the entire cab onto the other car frame or landing. The auxiliary racks (58a, 58b) may be mounted on a common auxiliary rack member (58), or may be separate. The auxiliary motorized pinions (55, 56, 57) may be bidirectional, or may be; and auxiliary pinions (32C, 33C, 34C) may be; mounted on the same shaft with main pinions (32b, 33b, 34b).

column12: Emergency elevator cab commandeering shuttle
column13: A particular elevator (1-9) is commandeered to transfer an emergency cab F to (or near) a floor where an alarm has been sounded. The commandeered car is brought to the floor FF where the emergency cab is parked. The fire cab is exchanged for the normal cab C on the commandeered car, and is then carried to (or near) the alarm floor for responding to the alarm. Passengers in the normal cab may exit through landing doorways (23). Emergency personnel have access to the alarm area through emergency hoistway doors (27). A rack and pinion horizontal motive means for moving the cabs is illustrated (FIG. 12 ).

column12: Car dispatching method between multi-deck elevator car frame shuttles
column13: An elevator system provides service between a ground level and each of three upper levels through a single elevator shuttle hoistway system. Three elevator cabs (B,D,F) are moved in a triple deck elevator car frame, or a four deck elevator car frame (75) in a low hoistway (51); two cabs (A,C) are moved in a double deck elevator car frame or four deck car frame (76) in a mid hoistway (52); and one cab (P) is moved in a single deck car frame or triple deck car frame (77) in a high hoistway (53). Other embodiments have other car frame arrangements.

column12: Elevator shuttle with auxiliary elevators at terminals
column13: Elevator cabs A-C move upwardly through three or more contiguous overlapping hoistways 38-40 in the upper decks of double deck car frames 41-43, and move downwardly through the hoistways in the lower decks (or vice versa). To switch between decks, the cabs are offloaded from the hoistways into auxiliary elevators 50, 51 at the terminal ends of the shuttle, and are moved to be adjacent to the other deck by the auxiliary elevator and loaded thereon for the trip in the opposite direction. A second embodiment has additional auxiliary elevators 64, 65 and additional cabs D, E so that loading and unloading of passengers do not delay movement of the cabs in the hoistways.

column12: Synchronizing elevator arrival at a level of a building
column13: The arrival of each of four dual-hoistway shuttle elevators S1-S4 is synchronized with a selected one of ten local elevators L1-L10, or ten low rise elevators L1-L10 and ten high rise elevators H1-H10 at a transfer floor 26 by limiting 140 the speed of the shuttle, gradually 149, or rapidly 154, 155 decreasing the speed of the shuttle, delaying a local elevator by holding its doors open for extra time, or controlling the speed of a local elevator, by cancelling or avoiding hall calls. Empty local elevators may be allowed to remain at the high end of the building, or compelled to travel to the lobby if needed. Elevators approaching a transfer floor may be synchronized by adjusting the speed of one of them until the remaining distance is the same for both. Hall calls may be prevented, cancelled, or negatively biased in dependence upon the tardiness of a local elevator. Synchronization may be achieved between shuttle elevators and local elevators, between portions of multi-hoistway shuttle elevators, and amongst elevator combinations employing three or more hoistways.

column12: Transferring elevator cabs between non-contiguous hoistways
column13: A plurality of express shuttle elevators S1-S4 exchange elevator cabs at a transfer floor 26 with local elevators L1-L10 by means of a carriage 107, the casters of which 93 are guided by tracks 70-83. A controller (Figs. 10-13) keeps track of the progress of the cabs from one elevator to another.

column12: SHUTTLE ELEVATOR PROVIDED WITH LOCAL ELEVATOR
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a shuttle elevator which is provided with a local elevator and serves in a plurality of continuous floors in a building. SOLUTION: A plurality of express shuttle elevators exchange an elevator car cage with a local elevator by means of a carriage means 107 on a transfer floor. A caster 93 of the carriage 107 is guided by means of a track 70. On the transfer floor, a linear induction motor LIM primary segment 60 is arranged, while a LIM secondary 128 is arranged in the carriage 107 for propelling it. In transfer, the carriage 107 is locked in the transfer floor, and a plurality of car cages are firmly locked 131 in the carriage 107 while they are moved. A controller holds a track through which the car cage moves from one elevator to another one.

column12: Pretorque to unload elevator car/floor locks before retraction
column13: To prevent elevator rope stretch effects when a horizontally transferable elevator cab is rolled onto and off of an elevator car frame, an elevator car/floor lock includes a bolt which extends across the interface between the car frame and the building and engages a strike. Jack screw and solenoid embodiments are shown. To take the weight off the lock bolts so that they may be retracted to permit moving the car frame vertically in the hoistway, strain gages or load sensors provided in or adjacent the bolts sense the weight supported thereby, and a pretorque program provides armature current to the hoisting motor to raise or lower the car frame sufficiently to reduce the load on the bolts to nil.

column12: Moving freight with passenger shuttle elevators
column13: The hoistways of passenger shuttle elevators are provided with freight landings (78) adjacent commercial businesses in the higher floors of a tall building; passenger cabs (71) are exchanged for freight containers (73) on the car frames (48) of the shuttle elevators, and the shuttle elevators are utilized to move the containers of freight from a freight receiving area (68) at the lower end of the building to the respective freight landings (78). In one embodiment, a ballast weight (80) is loaded onto a car frame as a container of freight is offloaded from the car frame so that the car frame may return to the freight receiving area for another container of freight, without the elevator being misbalanced. Another embodiment utilizes one of two decks for carrying containers of freight while the other deck carries an empty passenger cab, thereby to reduce the difference between the heaviest and lightest that the car frame will be as it returns empty to the freight receiving area for a subsequent container of freight. Another embodiment uses compound or other extensive roping and an extra large traction machine to permit returning a totally empty car frame to pick up a subsequent freight container.

column12: CAR OPERATED SAFETY GATE FOR HORIZONTALLY TRANSFERRABLE ELEVATOR CAB

column12: Fail-safe movement of elevator cabs between car frames and landings
column13: A first slidable auxiliary pinion (58a) on the bottom of a horizontally moveable elevator cab A disposed on a car frame (14) or a landing is moved out from under the cab toward another car frame (13) or landing by means of a motorized pinion (56) until it engages a motorized pinion (57) on the adjacent car frame (13) or landing, which then pulls the auxiliary pinion and the entire cab toward the other car frame or landing until a main rack (45) fixed to the bottom of the cab engages a motorized pinion (34) on the other car frame (13) or landing, which pinion then pulls the entire cab onto the other car frame or landing. The auxiliary racks (58a, 58b) may be mounted on a common auxiliary rack member (58), or may be separate. The auxiliary motorized pinions (55, 56, 57) may be bidirectional, or may be unidirectional and mounted on the same shaft with main pinions (32a, 32c; 33a, 33c; 34a, 34c).

column12: Synchronizing elevator arrival at a level of a building
column13: The arrival of each of four dual-hoistway shuttle elevators S1-S4 is synchronized with a selected one of ten local elevators L1-L10, or ten low rise elevators L1-L10 and ten high rise elevators H1-H10 at a transfer floor 26 by limiting 140 the speed of the shuttle, gradually 149, or rapidly 154, 155 decreasing the speed of the shuttle, delaying a local elevator by holding its doors open for extra time, or controlling the speed of a local elevator, by cancelling or avoiding hall calls. Empty local elevators may be allowed to remain at the high end of the building, or compelled to travel to the lobby if needed. Elevators approaching a transfer floor may be synchronized by adjusting the speed of one of them until the remaining distance is the same for both. Hall calls may be prevented, cancelled, or negatively biased in dependence upon the tardiness of a local elevator. Synchronization may be achieved between shuttle elevators and local elevators, between portions of multi-hoistway shuttle elevators, and amongst elevator combinations employing three or more hoistways.

column12: PRETORQUE TO UNLOAD ELEVATOR CAR/FLOOR LOCKS BEFORE RETRACTION
column13: To prevent elevator rope stretch effects when a horizontally transferable elevator cab (18) is rolled onto and off of an elevator car frame (10), an elevator car/floor lock (31) includes a bolt (47) which extends across the interface between the car frame and the building and engages a strike (39). Jack screw (44) and solenoid (60) embodiments are shown. To take the weight off the lock bolts so that they may be retracted to permit moving the car frame vertically in the hoistway, strain gages (64, 65) or load sensors (62, 63) provided in or adjacent the bolts sense the weight supported thereby, and a pretorque program (Fig. 6) provides armature current to the hoisting motor to raise or lower the car frame sufficiently to reduce the load on the bolts to nil.

column13: A particular elevator is commandeered to transfer an emergency cab F to (or near) a floor where an alarm has been sounded. column12: ELEVATOR CAGE MOVING DEVICE AND METHOD THEREOF
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a method and a device by which an elevator cage is moved from one of a group of elevators to another by moving an elevator cage between elevator car frames arranged in the unadjacent hoistway and exchanging a pair of cages mutually. SOLUTION: In a plurality of express shuttle elevators, an elevator cage is exchanged on a transfer floor provided with a local elevator by means of a carriage 107, and its caster 93 is guided by means of a track 70. On the transfer floor, a primary side segment 60 of a linear motor LIM is arranged, while a secondary side 128 of the linear motor LIM is arranged in the carriage 107 so as to propel the carriage 107. For installation, the carriage 107 can be locked 91 on the transfer floor, and in the case of transfer, the cage can be locked 131 on the carriage 107 for stabilization.

column12: ELEVATOR SHUTTLE SYSTEM AND OPERATION METHOD IN ELEVATOR SHUTTLE
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide three or more elevator hoist ways overlapped and being close to each other, arranged for plural elevator cars including moving cabs, and each having a double-deck car frame and arranged. SOLUTION: Elevator cabs A to C moves upward along three or more hoist ways 38 to 40 overlapped and being close to each other for the upper decks of double-deck car frames 41 to 43 and moves downward along hoist ways for the lower decks. In order to switch these decks to each other, the cabs are unloaded from the hoist ways to auxiliary elevators 50 and 51 at the ends of the shuttle, shifted so as to be adjacent to other decks by the auxiliary elevators, and then loaded on the auxiliary elevators so as to be oppositely shifted. Even the addition of other auxiliary elevators and cabs causes no delay in the getting-into or -off of occupants by the movement of the cabs in the hoist ways.

column12: ARRIVAL SYNCHRONIZING METHOD FOR ELEVATOR
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide an arrival synchronizing method for an elevator by which arrival of a plurality of elevator cars at a building level is synchronized and mutual exchange of a plurality of cars can be facilitated. SOLUTION: Arrival of four overlapping hoistway shuttle elevators S1-S4 at a building level 29 is synchronized with arrival of one selected from ten local elevators, ten lower level elevators L1-L10, and higher level elevators H1-H10. An empty local elevator is allowed to remain in a high end part of a building or transferred to a lobby if necessary. Elevators approaching a transfer floor are synchronized with each other when their speeds are regulated so that their remaining distances are equalized to each other. A hall calling is prevented or canceled independently of the local elevator. Synchronization is carried out between the shuttle elevator and the local elevator, between multiple elevating path shuttle elevators, and between combinations of elevators using three or more elevating paths.

column12: Horizontal and vertical passenger transport
column13: Elevator cabs are transferred between elevators, which may be shuttles, in various levels of a building, such as transport floors, in response to car calls registered in the cabs and hall calls registered on the transport floors. The cabs may be transferred from carriages or bogeys onto elevator car frames in a lateral direction, which is perpendicular to the motion of the cab on a carriage or bogey, or in a longitudinal direction which is the same as the direction of motion of a cab on a carriage or bogey. The horizontal/vertical control and transfer may be effected in response to the arrival at transport floors of elevators having cabs therein, or in response to the arrival at an elevator of a bogey carrying a cab which must be transported between a transport floor on one level of a building and a transport floor on another level of a building, in order to serve the need of a car call registered therein or a hall call. The horizontal transportation may occur on transport floors within a building, or may extend between different building segments or between different buildings.

column12: ELEVATOR OPERATING METHOD AND ELEVATOR SHUTTLE SYSTEM
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To reduce a building core space by comprising overlapping close hoist ways and continuously carrying cage cab, which are smaller in number by one than lower hoist ways next to a shuttle, to multiple car frames. SOLUTION: When passengers get on cage cabs 34-36 on an underground level 42, a triple deck car frame 29 is lifted to a first level 47. Then, the cage cab 34 is left in the triple deck car frame 29 on the first level 47, while the cage cabs 35, 36 are moved to a double deck car frame 30 so as to be transferred to the upper side of a building. Similarly, the cage cab 35 is left in the double deck car frame 30 on a second level 48, while the cage cab 36 is transferred to a single deck car frame 31. Subsequently, the cage cab 36 is finally arrives at a landing on the third level 49 in the building, and then, the passengers get off and other passengers get on the cage cab 36. Afterward, the cage cabs 34-36 are transferred to the underground level 42 by the inverse principle of that for the upward transfer, so that sufficient shift of the shuttle is completed.

column12: Transferring elevator cabs between non-contiguous hoistways
column13: A plurality of express shuttle elevators S1-S4 exchange elevator cabs at a transfer floor 26 with local elevators L1-L10 by means of a carriage 107, the casters of which 93 are guided by tracks 70-83. The transfer floor has linear induction motor (LIM) primary segments 60-67 disposed on the transfer floor; the carriage has a LIM secondary 128 thereon for propulsion. The carriages can be locked 91, 92 to the transfer floor for loading, and cabs can be locked 131 onto the carriages for stability when being moved. A controller (FIGS. 10-13) keeps track of the progress of the cabs from one elevator to another.

column12: FAIL-SAFE MOVEMENT OF ELEVATOR CABS BETWEEN CAR FRAMES AND LANDINGS
column13: A first slidable auxiliary pinion (58a) on the bottom of a horizontally moveable elevator cab A (Figs. 2-6) disposed on a car frame (14) or a landing is moved out from under the cab toward another car frame (13) or landing by means of a motorized pinion (56) until it engages a motorized pinion (57) on the adjacent car frame (13) or landing, which then pulls the auxiliary pinion and the entire cab toward the other car frame or landing until a main rack (45) fixed to the bottom of the cab engages a motorized pinion (34) on the other car frame (13) or landing, which pinion then pulls the entire cab onto the other car frame or landing. The auxiliary racks (58a, 58b) may be mounted on a common auxiliary rack member (58), or may be separate. The auxiliary motorized pinions (55, 56, 57) may be bidirectional, or may be unidirectional and mounted on the same shaft with main pinions (32a, 32c; 33a, 33c; 34a, 34c).

column12: Emergency elevator cab commandeering shuttle
column13: A particular elevator is commandeered to transfer an emergency cab F to (or near) a floor where an alarm has been sounded. The commandeered car is brought to the floor FF where the emergency cab is parked. The fire cab is exchanged for the normal cab C on the commandeered car, and is then carried to (or near) the alarm floor for responding to the alarm. Passengers in the normal cab may exit through landing doorways (23). Emergency personnel have access to the alarm area through emergency hoistway doors (27). A rack and pinion horizontal motive means for moving the cabs is illustrated.

column12: EXTRA DECK ELEVATOR SHUTTLE
column13: An elevator shuttle includes a plurality of elevator hoistways (14, 19, 24) which overlap, the elevator car frames (13, 21, 25) traveling in each hoistway including two decks per cab being carried by the car frame, plus an extra deck on car frames (20) in other than the highest (24) and lowest (14) hoistways. This allows cabs (C) traveling simultaneously, upwardly, in three or more hoistways to pass cabs (A, B) simultaneously traveling downwardly in those hoistways. The cabs may be loaded and unloaded while in the hoistway (Figs. 1, 13, 21) , or while in off-hoistway landing areas (Fig. 28). Embodiments include one cab per hoistway and two cabs per hoistway; three hoistways and four hoistways.

column12: Light emitting device with improved extraction efficiency

A surface of the substrate opposite the surface on which the semiconductor structure is grown is textured.

column12: Devices and methods for eliminating termite colonies
column13:
This invention relates to devices, kits, and methods for eliminating termite colonies. The kits, devices, and methods employ a termiticidal bait matrix containing 

   a) a termiticide selected such that the termiticide causes death to about 50 to about 100% of termites within about 24 to about 84 days after the termites begin to ingest the termiticide or the bait matrix comprising the termiticide, 

   b) a cellulose containing material, and 

   c) water. 

   The termiticidal bait matrix can be used in a bait station installed in the ground. The kits are suitable to be used by consumers in their homes.
